AREA HEALTH EDUCATION CENTERS (AHEC) PROGRAM - PROJECT TITLE: IDAHO AHEC PROGRAM OFFICE (IDAPO) APPLICANT SCHOOL ORGANIZATION NAME: IDAHO STATE UNIVERSITY DEPARTMENT: SCHOOL OF NURSING	  STATE: IDAHO ADDRESS:  IDAHO STATE UNIVERSITY, 921 S. 8TH AVENUE, STOP 8101, POCATELLO, IDAHO, 83209 PROJECT DIRECTOR NAME: DIANA C. SCHOW, PHD CONTACT PHONE NUMBERS: VOICE: 208-282-2477 FAX: 208-282-2946 EMAIL ADDRESS: SCHODIAN@ISU.EDU WEB SITE ADDRESS: HTTPS://WWW.ISU.EDU/SEIDAHEC/ TOTAL GRANT FUNDS REQUESTED: $3,750,000  PROGRAM PHASE: THE NEWLY PROPOSED IDAPO IS IN THE INFRASTRUCTURE DEVELOPMENT (ID) PHASE. IF FUNDED, IT WILL CONTINUE ACTIVITIES, UNINTERRUPTED, AT IDAHO’S THREE EXISTING CENTERS: NORTH IDAHO AHEC, SOUTHEAST IDAHO AHEC, AND SOUTHWEST IDAHO AHEC. IT WILL ALSO: 1) TRANSFER PREVIOUS PROGRAM OFFICE RESPONSIBILITIES FROM WASHINGTON AHEC TO IDAHO, HOUSED IN IDAHO STATE UNIVERSITY’S (ISU) ACCREDITED SCHOOL OF NURSING, 2) MOVE SOUTHEAST IDAHO AHEC OUT OF ISU TO SOUTHEASTERN IDAHO PUBLIC HEALTH, AND 3) ADD A PROPOSED, SOUTH CENTRAL IDAHO AHEC IN YEAR THREE OF THE FUNDING CYCLE. TWO PLANNING YEARS ARE REQUESTED FOR TRANSITION ACTIVITIES. GEOGRAPHIC AREA/TARGETED POPULATIONS:  RURAL AND UNDERSERVED POPULATIONS ACROSS THE STATE OF IDAHO ARE THIS PROJECT’S FOCUS. ADDING A FOURTH CENTER WILL INCREASE IDAPO’S CAPACITY TO REACH THESE POPULATIONS AND MEET WORKFORCE TRAINING NEEDS, ESPECIALLY COMMUNITY HEALTH WORKER TRAINING AND BEHAVIORAL HEALTH INTEGRATION EMPHASIZING THE CLINICAL PRIORITY OF IMPROVING BEHAVIORAL/MENTAL HEALTH ACCESS AND CARE. GOALS, MILESTONES AND OBJECTIVES: EACH YEAR BETWEEN 2022 AND 2027, IDAPO WILL WORK TOWARDS CREATING A DIVERSE AND CULTURALLY COMPETENT, EQUITABLY DISTRIBUTED WORKFORCE THAT IS WELL VERSED IN PRACTICE TRANSFORMATION AND PREPARED TO WORK IN RURAL AND UNDERSERVED AREAS. THE GOALS OF INCREASED VIABILITY, VISIBILITY, AND SUSTAINABILITY OF IDAPO WILL INVOLVE DEVELOPING STRATEGIC PARTNERSHIPS AND ADVISORY GROUPS TO FUND, SUSTAIN AND IMPROVE FOUR CORNERSTONE ACTIVITIES HIGH LIGHTING HRSA PRIORITY TOPICS: 1) THE IDAHO AHEC SCHOLARS PROGRAM, WHICH WILL TRAIN INTERPROFESSIONAL COHORTS OF 15 HEALTH PROFESSIONS STUDENTS ANNUALLY PER CENTER, 2) COMMUNITY-BASED EXPERIENTIAL TRAINING OPPORTUNITIES, LIKE THE RURAL-UNDERSERVED OPPORTUNITIES PROGRAM (RUOP), WHICH WILL SUPPORT FIELD PLACEMENTS, PRECEPTORSHIPS AND OTHER COMMUNITY-BASED ACTIVITIES FOR 20 HEALTH PROFESSIONS STUDENTS ANNUALLY AND PREPARE THEM TO BECOME PROVIDERS IN IDAHO’S HIGH-NEEDS AREAS, 3) FOUR TO EIGHT CONTINUING EDUCATION ACTIVITIES PROVIDED ANNUALLY FOR PRACTICING HEALTH PROFESSIONALS THAT WILL ADDRESS RELEVANT HEALTH ISSUES, AND 4) PATHWAY ACTIVITIES FOR AT LEAST 150 STUDENTS ANNUALLY IN GRADES 9-12 THAT WILL EMPHASIZE PUBLIC HEALTH. OVERVIEW OF PROGRAM PLAN: IDAPO SEEKS TO ADDRESS WORKFORCE SHORTAGES IN PRIMARY CARE, DENTAL, AND MENTAL HEALTH CARE AND MEET SPECIFIC COMMUNITY NEEDS AROUND THE STATE. IT WILL BRING AN IDAHO-CENTRIC FOCUS TO INCREASING THE NUMBER OF HEALTH PROFESSIONS STUDENTS WHO PURSUE CAREERS IN PRIMARY CARE AND MENTAL HEALTH AND ARE PREPARED TO PRACTICE IN RURAL AND UNDERSERVED AREAS. IT WILL IMPLEMENT HEALTH WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITIES, FUNCTION AS THE STATE’S HUB FOR AHEC CENTERS, ENSURE A QUALITY STATEWIDE EVALUATION PLAN, AND LEVERAGE EXISTING STRATEGIC PARTNERSHIPS WITH ORGANIZATIONS LIKE THE IDAHO PRIMARY CARE ASSOCIATION TO ENSURE SUSTAINABILITY. PROJECT EVALUATION PLAN: THROUGH REGULAR COMMUNICATION USING A RAPID-CYCLE ASSESSMENT PROCESS, IDAPO AND AHEC CENTERS WILL COMPLETE FORMATIVE AND SUMMATIVE EVALUATIONS USING METHODS SUCH AS PRE-POST SURVEYS AND INTERVIEWS TO EVALUATE INDIVIDUAL AND AGGREGATE OUTCOMES ON DIVERSITY, DISTRIBUTION AND PRACTICE TRANSFORMATION IN IDAHO. YEAR-OVER-YEAR GAINS WILL BE SOUGHT IN NUMBER AND TYPE OF PARTICIPANTS, SATISFACTION, KNOWLEDGE, APPLICATION, AND IMPACT. EVALUATION ACTIVITIES WILL ALSO FOCUS ON THE SUPPLY AND DISTRIBUTION OF THE STATE’S HEALTH WORKFORCE. ALL DATA WILL BE COLLECTED A
